window.NETPLUS_LESSONS_W3 = {"1":{"title":"Hubs, Bridges & Switches","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"3\" data-day=\"1\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 3 · Day 1</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">Hubs, Bridges &amp; Switches</h2></header><h3>Hubs</h3>\n<p>A hub repeats all traffic.</p>\n<p>Problems:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>One collision domain</li>\n<li>Inefficient</li>\n<li>No intelligence</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Switches</h2>\n<p>Switches learn MAC addresses.</p>\n<p>Advantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Separate collision domains</li>\n<li>Improved performance</li>\n<li>Full duplex</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>MAC Address Table</h2>\n<p>Switches store:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>MAC address</li>\n<li>Interface</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Commands:</p>\n<pre class=\"code-block\"><code class=\"language-bash\">show mac address-table\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Expanded notes: Collision vs broadcast domains</h3>\n\n<p>A <strong>collision domain</strong> is a segment where a collision could occur on shared media. Classic hubs put every port in one domain. Modern switches isolate each port (full duplex), so collisions are rare on switched Ethernet.</p>\n<p>A <strong>broadcast domain</strong> is the set of devices that receive a broadcast frame (destination FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF). One VLAN = one broadcast domain unless routing is used between VLANs.</p>\n<div class=\"callout-inline tip\"><strong>Exam tip:</strong> \"Which device reduces collision domains?\" → Switch. \"Which device separates broadcast domains?\" → Router or VLAN.</div>\n\n<h4>Quick review questions</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Define the main term for this lesson in your own words.</li>\n<li>Which layer or device is involved?</li>\n<li>What command or tool would you use to verify it?</li>\n<li>What is one misconfiguration symptom?</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Evolution from hubs to switches. Collision vs broadcast domains, MAC table, half/full duplex.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>Hubs, Bridges &amp; Switches</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which device separates collision domains? Broadcast domains?</li><li>What command displays the MAC address table on a Cisco switch?</li><li>How does a router differ from a switch when forwarding traffic?</li><li>Compare stateful vs stateless firewall behavior.</li><li>What is the purpose of a default route (0.0.0.0/0)?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Device identification quiz: 15 scenario questions matching devices to network problems (e.g., &quot;Which device reduces collision domains?&quot;).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Design a small business network diagram showing correct device placement (switch, router, firewall, AP, servers) with written justification.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> 2-switch, 1-router topology: hostnames, passwords, trunk links. Verify with show commands.</p>\n</section></article>"},"2":{"title":"Routers & Layer 3","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"3\" data-day=\"2\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 3 · Day 2</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">Routers &amp; Layer 3</h2></header><h3>Router Functions</h3>\n<p>Routers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Connect networks</li>\n<li>Route packets</li>\n<li>Use routing tables</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Routing Decisions</h2>\n<p>Routers examine:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Destination IP</li>\n<li>Routing table</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Then forward packets.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Default Route</h2>\n<p>Used when no specific route exists.</p>\n<pre class=\"code-block\"><code class=\"language-bash\">ip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 10.0.0.1\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Expanded notes: Routing decisions</h3>\n\n<p>Routers never forward by MAC alone across subnets—they decapsulate to Layer 3, match destination IP to routing table, then re-encapsulate on the outbound interface.</p>\n<p><strong>Longest prefix match</strong> chooses the most specific route when multiple entries exist. <strong>Administrative distance</strong> breaks ties between protocol sources (connected beats static beats OSPF, etc.).</p>\n\n<h4>Quick review questions</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Define the main term for this lesson in your own words.</li>\n<li>Which layer or device is involved?</li>\n<li>What command or tool would you use to verify it?</li>\n<li>What is one misconfiguration symptom?</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Forwarding decisions, routing tables, directly connected routes. Default and static routing overview.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>Routers &amp; Layer 3</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which device separates collision domains? Broadcast domains?</li><li>What command displays the MAC address table on a Cisco switch?</li><li>How does a router differ from a switch when forwarding traffic?</li><li>Compare stateful vs stateless firewall behavior.</li><li>What is the purpose of a default route (0.0.0.0/0)?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Device identification quiz: 15 scenario questions matching devices to network problems (e.g., &quot;Which device reduces collision domains?&quot;).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Design a small business network diagram showing correct device placement (switch, router, firewall, AP, servers) with written justification.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> 2-switch, 1-router topology: hostnames, passwords, trunk links. Verify with show commands.</p>\n</section></article>"},"3":{"title":"Firewalls, IDS/IPS & Load Balancers","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"3\" data-day=\"3\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 3 · Day 3</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">Firewalls, IDS/IPS &amp; Load Balancers</h2></header><h3>Firewalls</h3>\n<p>Filter traffic.</p>\n<p>Types:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Stateless</li>\n<li>Stateful</li>\n<li>Next-generation</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>IDS vs IPS</h2>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>IDS</th>\n<th>IPS</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Detects</td>\n<td>Detects and blocks</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Passive</td>\n<td>Active</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Load Balancers</h2>\n<p>Distribute traffic across servers.</p>\n<p>Benefits:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Redundancy</li>\n<li>Performance</li>\n<li>Scalability</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Expanded notes: Perimeter security</h3>\n\n<p><strong>Stateful firewalls</strong> track connection state so return traffic for permitted outbound sessions is allowed automatically. <strong>Stateless</strong> filters each packet in isolation.</p>\n<p><strong>NGFW</strong> adds application awareness, IPS integration, and identity context beyond port/protocol filtering.</p>\n\n<h4>Quick review questions</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Define the main term for this lesson in your own words.</li>\n<li>Which layer or device is involved?</li>\n<li>What command or tool would you use to verify it?</li>\n<li>What is one misconfiguration symptom?</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Stateful vs stateless firewalls, perimeter security, ACL overview. IDS vs IPS differences.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>Firewalls, IDS/IPS &amp; Load Balancers</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which device separates collision domains? Broadcast domains?</li><li>What command displays the MAC address table on a Cisco switch?</li><li>How does a router differ from a switch when forwarding traffic?</li><li>Compare stateful vs stateless firewall behavior.</li><li>What is the purpose of a default route (0.0.0.0/0)?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Device identification quiz: 15 scenario questions matching devices to network problems (e.g., &quot;Which device reduces collision domains?&quot;).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Design a small business network diagram showing correct device placement (switch, router, firewall, AP, servers) with written justification.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> 2-switch, 1-router topology: hostnames, passwords, trunk links. Verify with show commands.</p>\n</section></article>"},"4":{"title":"Wireless Access Points","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"3\" data-day=\"4\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 3 · Day 4</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">Wireless Access Points</h2></header><h3>AP Functions</h3>\n<p>Provide wireless connectivity.</p>\n<p>Concepts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>SSID</li>\n<li>Channels</li>\n<li>Frequency bands</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>2.4 GHz vs 5 GHz</h2>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>2.4 GHz</th>\n<th>5 GHz</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Longer range</td>\n<td>Faster</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>More interference</td>\n<td>Less interference</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 3, Day 4</strong> (Wireless Access Points), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Infrastructure vs ad-hoc, SSID, BSS/ESS. WLC concept, fat vs thin APs.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>Wireless Access Points</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which device separates collision domains? Broadcast domains?</li><li>What command displays the MAC address table on a Cisco switch?</li><li>How does a router differ from a switch when forwarding traffic?</li><li>Compare stateful vs stateless firewall behavior.</li><li>What is the purpose of a default route (0.0.0.0/0)?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Device identification quiz: 15 scenario questions matching devices to network problems (e.g., &quot;Which device reduces collision domains?&quot;).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Design a small business network diagram showing correct device placement (switch, router, firewall, AP, servers) with written justification.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> 2-switch, 1-router topology: hostnames, passwords, trunk links. Verify with show commands.</p>\n</section></article>"},"5":{"title":"Switch Configuration Lab","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"3\" data-day=\"5\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 3 · Day 5</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">Switch Configuration Lab</h2></header><h3>Basic Commands</h3>\n<pre class=\"code-block\"><code class=\"language-bash\">hostname SW1\nenable secret Cisco123\nbanner motd #Unauthorized access prohibited#\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n<h2>Port Security Intro</h2>\n<pre class=\"code-block\"><code class=\"language-bash\">switchport port-security\nswitchport port-security maximum 2\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 3, Day 5</strong> (Switch Configuration Lab), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>CLI basics: hostname, banners, passwords, enable/disable ports, port security intro.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>Switch Configuration Lab</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which device separates collision domains? Broadcast domains?</li><li>What command displays the MAC address table on a Cisco switch?</li><li>How does a router differ from a switch when forwarding traffic?</li><li>Compare stateful vs stateless firewall behavior.</li><li>What is the purpose of a default route (0.0.0.0/0)?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Device identification quiz: 15 scenario questions matching devices to network problems (e.g., &quot;Which device reduces collision domains?&quot;).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Design a small business network diagram showing correct device placement (switch, router, firewall, AP, servers) with written justification.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> 2-switch, 1-router topology: hostnames, passwords, trunk links. Verify with show commands.</p>\n</section></article>"}};
